5.3
â³ Longevity vs. Healthy Longevity
Modern medicine has succeeded in extending life expectancy â€” but not always in extending vitality. We live longer, yet often with more chronic conditions. Longevity without prevention can mean more years spent in waiting rooms, more calendars filled with treatments rather than experiences.
Prevention changes the equation. Medicine may add years to life, but prevention adds life to those years. Without it, health becomes only a pause between therapies. With it, aging is not a burden but a rhythm sustained with clarity and strength.
In short: extending the calendar is not enough; prevention extends the quality of the days.

